The Henhouse

The problem Sotheby=E2=80=99s faces is that ex-employees, like the ones gat=
hered at Redden=E2=80=99s memorial, are busy spinning up different scenario=
s to explain the Emiratis=E2=80=99 foot-dragging, and as you can imagine, n=
one of them is good. At the same time, there=E2=80=99s been a real talent d=
rain, with a long summer of departures including the principal auctioneer i=
n Hong Kong, the vice chairman for institutional sales, the S.V.P. of globa=
l proposals, the head of African and Oceanic art, the head of Sotheby=E2=80=
=99s Zurich, the head of client strategy in the Americas, and the global he=
ad of dispute resolution. In the past few weeks, some key support staff als=
o left the company, demoralizing many of the specialists who liked them per=
sonally and would have relied upon them in the coming months of high-profil=
e sales.

Speculation surrounds the C-suite, too. The
news last month that Sotheby=E2=80=99s C.F.O. Jean-Luc Berrebi, one of Drah=
i=E2=80=99s most trusted executives, would be stepping down ( https://puck.=
news/can-patrick-drahi-maintain-control-of-sothebys/?utm_campaign=3DWall+Po=
wer+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2810%2F1%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+=
%2810%2F1%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_te=
rm=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) set off speculation about the fate of C.E.O. Char=
lie Stewart. (Many Drahi watchers point out that he likes to move his execu=
tives around.) But Stewart has been the face of Sotheby=E2=80=99s for some =
time now, and he is intimately associated with the new fee structure and th=
e company=E2=80=99s investments, especially in real estate. He also collabo=
rated on a long profile with ARTnews that was recently published in its Top=
 200 Collectors issue. That=E2=80=99s hardly the sign of an executive getti=
ng ready for a move.

Finally, of course, there is the much-discussed fate of the
Breuer building. Sotheby=E2=80=99s maintains the deal on the building was a=
lways slated to close some time this fall. But the longer it takes, the mor=
e people start wondering whether Larry Gagosian=E2=80=94who has to move out=
 of his flagship gallery location nearby=E2=80=94will somehow swoop in and =
buy the building out from under Drahi. The Breuer, home of the Whitney Muse=
um from 1966 to 2014, lacks a loading dock, which is kind of a problem for =
anyone putting on a high volume of shows. As a piece of commercial real est=
ate, though, it=E2=80=99s not really valuable to anyone but Drahi or Gagosi=
an. (For some, Gagosian would be in a better position to utilize the space =
throughout the year.)

I may have been watching way too much of HBO=E2=80=99s Industry, but the Ma=
chiavellian part of my brain sometimes half wonders if the Emiratis are not=
 playing out some melodramatic plot where they push Sotheby=E2=80=99s to th=
e brink by delaying the payment only to swoop in and buy it all on the chea=
p.
If I were writing this for Industry, I=E2=80=99d contemplate someone like A=
lexander Klabin, the former hedge fund manager lurking quietly on Sotheby=
=E2=80=99s cap table with a small ownership stake, also putting in a bid. A=
nd, of course, there are the former suitors who lost out to Drahi that migh=
t reemerge to make a run at the trophy property.

But as much as I think it would greatly help Sotheby=E2=80=99s for the Emir=
atis or Drahi to do something definitive to rebuild confidence, like close =
on the Breuer building or announce some sort of bridge loan until the deal =
closes, I suspect everything will continue to muddle through until the play=
ers turn over their final cards.

