x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Even the Emiratis=
=E2=80=99 cash, which can=E2=80=99t come soon enough, won=E2=80=99t necessa=
rily fix Sotheby=E2=80=99s problems. The house=E2=80=99s new fee structure =
is still unproven. Yes, lowering the buyer=E2=80=99s premium should be good=
 for consignors, especially since the old fees could add as much as 35 perc=
ent (along with sales tax) to the hammer price. But even if this was the ri=
ght decision=E2=80=94and executives inside Christie=E2=80=99s and Phillips =
are certainly trying to convince plenty of sellers that it wasn=E2=80=99t=
=E2=80=94Sotheby=E2=80=99s would have been wiser to time the transition to =
when its financial position was stronger and the market was on the upswing.=
 <br/><br/>Last week, as I previously noted, the New York mid-season sales =
were pretty much comparable between Sotheby=E2=80=99s and Christie=E2=80=99=
s. Sotheby=E2=80=99s sold $33 million worth of art in New York; Christie=E2=
=80=99s sold $29.9 million today.
Though Sotheby=E2=80=99s did have a much better hammer ratio for their sale=
s, which could validate their pitch for the new fees even though, as I was =
reminded by a longtime auction watcher, much of the property in those sales=
 had been held over from previous auctions. They were the smaller lots from=
 the bigger estate sales that had nowhere else to be sold. <br/><br/>The ca=
talogs for the Frieze sales in London next week tell a different story. Sot=
heby=E2=80=99s has =C2=A334 million in presale value in its London evening =
sale; Christie=E2=80=99s has =C2=A373 million, more than twice as much. In =
the contemporary day sales, it=E2=80=99s =C2=A34 million at Sotheby=E2=80=
=99s and =C2=A311 million at Christie=E2=80=99s, an even greater disparity.=
 <br/><br/>Is this a sign that the new fee structure is holding back consig=
nments? Truthfully, there are many factors that could explain the disparity=
, including the decline of the London market and Sotheby=E2=80=99s previous=
 decision to move more resources to Paris. But, alas, those figures
<i>don=E2=80=99t</i> combat the impression among art advisors and rival hou=
ses=E2=80=94not to mention current and former employees=E2=80=94that Sotheb=
y=E2=80=99s is in the middle of a skid. <br/></td>
         </tr>
